english:
  title: Memorial to the Respectful and Yielding King
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your humble servant, Jeong Do-jeon, Court Scholar of the Political Chamber, having respectfully read Your Majesty's edict, observes that you watch carefully for changes in the heavens above, and seek counsel from your subjects below, taking upon yourself responsibility through eight matters of self-examination. Having read this twice and thrice, your servant cannot restrain his admiration. That Your Highness attributes Heaven's warnings to yourself, opens wide the path for remonstrance, and hopes to hear of your shortcomings—this exceeds even what the ancient sage-kings achieved.

    Your servant, bearing the title of Prime Minister, has offered no aid or instruction, bringing worry upon the throne. That you have sent repeated and earnest exhortations troubles your servant greatly. It has been said that the sovereign is the head, and ministers are the limbs. Compared to the human body, we are indeed one organism. Thus when the sovereign calls, the minister responds; when the sovereign speaks, the minister listens—some saying "this may be," others saying "this may not be"—all working toward good governance. Yet if Heaven sends calamity, it is the ministers who have caused it. In ancient times, when disasters struck, the Three Excellencies would request their dismissal, and great ministers would likewise step aside. Your servant requests release from office to dispel these calamities. Yet ancient ministers, when requesting retirement, always offered words of admonition. How much more should your servant, now receiving this edict, not attempt to contribute some modest insight?

    Your Majesty's edict asks: "Is my shallow virtue unrefined, failing to win Heaven's heart? Do administrative shortcomings leave the people's hopes unmet?" Your servant understands this thus: Virtue is attainment—attainment of the heart. Governance is rectification—rectification of the self. Yet virtue has two sources: that which one receives from natural endowment, and that which one gains through cultivation. Your Highness possesses vast generosity and innate compassion—these are gifts of natural endowment. Yet you have not devoted yourself to studying the classics to examine the methods of sages, nor have you gained experience in affairs to understand the urgent matters of the age. How then can your servant assure you that virtue is necessarily perfected and governance necessarily without flaw?

    The Han Emperor Cheng appeared majestic and solemn upon the throne, yet could not prevent the Han from falling. The Liang Emperor Wu wept and refused food when executing criminals, earning praise for compassion, yet could not save Jiangnan from chaos. They possessed natural excellence but lacked the cultivation of virtue and governance. Your servant humbly urges: do not rely upon your natural gifts, but take as warning what remains uncultivated. Then virtue will flourish and governance will succeed.

    Your Majesty's edict asks: "Have those appointed served private interest? Have rewards and punishments departed from righteousness?" Your servant believes: whether appointments stem from public or private motives, only Your Highness can know. Yet once appointments are announced, the people speak, saying "this one is a old friend, that one is a relative by marriage." Such external discussion troubles your servant, fearing private interest has mingled therein. Rewards encourage merit; punishments deter crime. We call rewards "Heaven's mandate" and punishments "Heaven's chastisement," for Heaven entrusts these powers to the sovereign to administer on Heaven's behalf. Though these emerge from the ruler, they are not instruments for the ruler's private use.

    Since Your Highness assumed the throne, among those who have received rewards and punishments, there are cases where the deeds were identical yet the outcomes differed. Kim Ju spoke one truth, yet one received extreme punishment while another received promotion. Kim Jong-yeon's escape from prison was one crime, yet one guard was executed while another was employed. Their conspiracy to aid the escape was the same, yet among the accomplices, some live while others die. Your servant cannot discern: if those who received capital punishment truly had guilt, what fortune befell those promoted to office? If those promoted truly had no guilt, what crime did those executed commit?

    U and Chang seized the throne of our Wang house—they are truly traitors to the royal ancestors, enemies to all people and subjects. Yet their relatives and associates received no punishment. Should they not be banished to distant lands to satisfy the hearts of both heaven and earth? Long ago, when Wu Zetian, as the High Ancestor's consort, seized her son Emperor Zhongzong's throne, the Five Marshals rose in righteousness, overthrew Wu, and restored Zhongzong. Though Wu was mother and Zhongzong was son, the historian still criticized the Five Marshals for not executing the perpetrator and exterminating her clan entirely. How much more should those like U and Chang, who lack Wu's kinship yet possess Wu's crimes, and whose relatives and associates exceed Wu's lineage, face justice?

    When the Remonstrance Officials recently memorialized that these men be banished, your servant hoped this might at least soothe the ancestors' and people's resentment. Yet within months, they all received imperial favor and gathered in the capital, coming and going freely. Though Your Highness has now yielded to the officials' words and banished some, there appears hesitation and reluctance. What principle governs this?

    When all the generals returned and proposed restoring the Wang house, this was Heaven repenting and the ancestors secretly arranging for Wang restoration—a heaven-sent opportunity. Yet some obstructed this, ultimately installing the false "Chang" to prevent Wang's return, and some plotted to restore Sinwu to permanently cut off Wang's line. These are rebel traitors, beyond the law's tolerance. That Your Highness spared their lives and placed them afar might be acceptable, yet now all have been recalled, comforted, and settled—as if their crimes were false accusations.

    The generals' knowledge that they obstructed the Wang house and installed the false "Chang" is common knowledge. They confessed directly, with clear evidence. That they received Sinwu to cut off Wang was testified by Kim Ju and Jeong Deuk-hu beforehand, and confirmed by I Rim and I Gwi-saeng afterward, with overwhelming corroboration. To call this false accusation—how could there then be any rebel or traitor worthy of punishment in all the realm?

    When human action fails to accord with justice, it necessarily accords with private affection. If Your Highness's action accords with justice, then U and Chang's followers are all ancestors' traitors. If it accords with private affection, then keeping their followers causes future trouble—as when Yun Yi and Yi Cho requested the prince command Heaven's armies. What benefit does this hold for human feeling?

    Some say: "To forgive the guilty brings immense grace; their strength shall later serve us, the people's hearts will naturally settle, and chaos will naturally cease." Your servant humbly contends: law and punishment exist to prevent chaos—upon which sovereigns depend for safety. Should law and punishment waver, the tools preventing chaos crumble first; strength arrives not, yet calamity does; the heart settles not, yet chaos does not cease. Allow your servant to illuminate this through the affair of Emperor Zhongzong and Wu Sansi.

    Wu Sansi was the most influential of Wu's faction. Though he was Zhongzong's mother's cousin, Zhongzong neither punished nor rejected him, treating him with great favor. Now consider: the Five Marshals, by establishing Wu's son as emperor, saved Sansi from the executioner's block. Thus they showed not only service to Zhongzong but granted Sansi a heaven-and-earth-recreating grace. Yet Sansi never considered this. Doubting his crimes would not be forgiven, day and night he slandered the Five Marshals: "Their power grows heavy; they rely on merit to bewitched the emperor." Zhongzong, believing Sansi loved him, drew him close; regarding the Five Marshals as powerful, he grew suspicious. The Marshals grew distant daily; Sansi grew intimate daily. Ultimately the Marshals were executed and Zhongzong murdered. Zhongzong's miscalculation amounted merely to this: "I could not protect my ministers." Yet how could he foresee his own death at Sansi's hand?

    As kinship goes, Sansi was his mother's cousin; as favor goes, he received his life preserved—yet gained neither gratitude nor loyalty, but only catastrophe. This shows how difficult it is to trust slanderers. Their initial scheme merely aims at self-preservation, yet unchecked wickedness leads them down a path that destroys others' bodies, ruins others' families and states, until they achieve their own ruin. Does Sansi differ from ancient or modern times?

    Heaven and humanity leave no space between them; fortune and calamity respond according to their kind. Now internally, officials perform their duties and commoners pursue their trades; externally, the greater realm remains at peace and distant peoples submit. From where would chaos arise? Yet when slanderers tangle affairs below, the signs of trouble appear above. The guest star enters the Purple Forbidden Enclosure—your servant fears Sansi walks at your side. The Fire Star enters the Ghost Palace—your servant fears the Sansi catastrophe approaches.

    Though your servant and others suffer harm comparable to the Five Marshals, we would not complain. Yet for the Wang house's established dynasty, we grieve. Should anyone say "such things will surely not occur; such speech is mere delusion," did Zhongzong not believe similarly? Yet he became the ancestor of later ridicule. Your servant fears the later age laughing at the present is like the present laughing at antiquity.

    Dong Zhongshu taught: "Heaven, loving its sovereign, first sends calamity as warning, hoping he will fear, reform, and reflect." Your servant humbly urges: when appointing or punishing people, do not first consider kinship or status, but uniformly examine whether merit or crime exists. Handle each case justly so none dominate others. Then appointments will be impartial, rewards and punishments will be just, human affairs will be correct, and Heaven's way will flow smoothly.

    Your Majesty's edict asks: "Has the people's suffering persisted while resources were wastefully spent? Have lower voices failed to reach above, leaving grievances unresolved? Who are the talented unrecognized? Who are the slanderers unchastised?" Your servant has heard that among the Three Departments' accounts, spending on Buddhist and spiritual matters predominates. Has wasteful expenditure ever exceeded this? Yet Buddhism's harm has ever been difficult to discern. Its adherents say: "This is good work, virtuous work. Those who turn to us see the nation grow rich and the people live long." Hearing this, rulers are pleased, expending all resources to flatter and serve Buddhist deities. Should anyone object, they respond: "I serve the Buddha; you oppose this? Thus I am good and you evil; I follow the Way and you follow demons. I serve Buddhism not for myself but to enrich the nation and extend the people's lives."

    Once this reasoning hardens in the heart, no other voice can penetrate. Since Your Highness's accession, meditation halls have risen higher than the palace, Buddhist assemblies perpetually meet in temples, Daoist rites proceed without season, and shamanic ceremonies occur without restraint. Your Highness believes these good works, not knowing they are not; believes they enrich the nation, not knowing the nation withers; believes they extend life, not knowing people suffer poverty. Though advisors speak, all are rejected as disobedience. This is precisely what your servant means: the doctrine of virtuous works and blessed longevity has already taken firm root in the heart.

    Once the Liang Emperor Wu debased his ten-thousand-chariot throne, thrice offering himself as a temple servant, exhausting Jiangnan's resources to erect great Buddha halls. Did his heart not believe this would bring benefit? Yet when the common man rose in rebellion, his body suffered humiliation, his descendants found no haven, and the realm fell with them. Where then was the Buddhism's promise of virtue rewarded and blessedness received?

    This concerns a distant age. Yet the Xuanzong Emperor revered Buddhism, personally performing disciples' rites before monks; the hundred high seats in the palace and the Manjushri Assembly at the演福 Temple occurred every year without fail; the Cloud Hermitage's gold and jade gleamed across valleys; the shadow temples' eaves soared to the heavens. Resources were exhausted, resentment arose, yet all were disregarded. One might say Buddha was served supremely, yet no blessing came. Is this not a brilliant mirror?

    In Zhou's final years, when divine beings descended at Youxin, the Grand Historian Guo said: "When a realm is about to rise, it heeds human counsel. When a realm is about to fall, it heeds spirits." Zhou indeed fell. Thus one may conclude: serving Buddha and serving spirits brings no benefit, only harm.

    Your servant humbly urges: command the officials to prohibit all unorthodox and defiling practices outside those in the official ritual canon. Then resources will be preserved and wastefully spent no more.

    Since Your Highness's accession, some who committed crimes went unpunished; some were released. It seems no grievances remain unresolved. Yet amnesty profits cunning men while harming the righteous; thus repeated amnesties reveal where grievances lie. Recently the Remonstrance Officials, raising matters of dynastic importance, were all banished. Your servant fears this is when grievances go unresolved and talents remain unrecognized.

    Regarding slanderers: their traces are hidden, their speech obscure, difficult to discern. Yet generally, when the sovereign errs, the righteous openly dispute; when others sin, the righteous openly reprove. Standing aloft, not mingling, maintaining principle, fearing no man's judgment—these mark the true gentleman. Those who hide their traces, fear exposure, remain silent in company, yet slander in private audience—these are slanderers. Your Highness, observing external officials and internal ministers through your servant's words, may readily discern the slanderer's nature.

    Though humans are most foolish, all know self-preservation; regarding family's welfare, who lacks such concern? Though your servant is called rash, he has not reached madness; surely he cherishes himself. Though your servant stands isolated amid universal resentment, knowing words spoken bring swift disaster, yet Your Highness asks without concealment. How could your servant not answer truthfully? This is why your servant prefers disaster's receipt to silence, prefers direct speech to evasion.

    Your servant humbly urges: attend to this matter and consider it, perceiving your servant's willingness to forget himself for the public good. Though death come ten thousand times, your servant harbors no regret.
